<Content>Ritzy Ritz Carlton ritz carlton bali: at $200 for deluxe (ie, standard) partial ocean view bookedthrough [--], incl. tax and breakfast. my husband thought it was adeal, cos of the level of amenities -- it's a truly luxurious resort on par withthe international best. was a splurge for us but well worth it: three extremelybeautiful pool areas. the main loungey pool is big, nice, infinity pool whereyou gaze out into the indian ocean. the beach pool is even better -- completelyunobstructed cliff view, and not too many people as the steps down and up are abit of a climb. at sunset, it's just unbeatable. the next morning we ventured tothe villa pool, a short 2 min. ride away on a cart/mini-van provided by thehotel. incredibly sculpted pool environment with several architecturallystunning pools, also not many people as it's used mainly by villa folks but opento all. the boutique there (and at the main hotel) is also nice. another 3 min.ride away is kubu beach, the tiny private beach operated by the hotel. wow. it'slike dreamlands or padang padang without the rocks and touts. completelyundisturbed piece of paradise, and, though small, the kind of beach you've beenlooking for all your life. after the 150 step climb up, the staff reward youwith ice cold water, much appreciated. our room at the ritz, although their mostbasic, was very nice, big enough, with veranda and partial ocean view. alsoseparate shower and basic bathtub. my hubby liked the personal safe in bothsofitel and ritz carlton (you can store your valuables in alam shanti's officesafe). breakfast, when we arrived, was full! they tried to steer us to anotherrestaurant but we waited and were shown a table 5 minutes later. the spread waslarge, mix of western, indonesian, japanese (clientele is at least 80% asian atthe ritz - jpse, korean and taiwanese- compared to the other hotels, sofitelmainly european and some american).expensive restos in hotel we didn't try, but breakfast spread is grand. we had seafood